- Virgulas Reference Document
  This document is the source of truth for "Virgulas", a local-first browser outliner.
  + It is an infinite list of editable "Nodes".
    - Each "Node" has a **single line** of text
    - Can have an optional text called "Description".
      Only the first 2 lines of the "Description" are visible when not editing, showing "..." otherwise
    - Can have "Children", which in turn are other "Nodes"
    - Each "Node" text and its "Description" can have rendered markdown when not editing.
      Markdown elements are limited to
      **Bold**, __Italic__, [links](http://example.com), ![](https://images.png), `monospace code`
      Rendered links always open in a new tab/window
    - Inline `#tags` and `@mentions` in rendered markdown appear as rounded pills
      Clicking/tapping a pill immediately opens Search with that token pre-filled
  + Behaviors of a "Node"
    + FOCUS
      - When focusing a "Node" or "Description", the text becomes editable, and the raw markdown is visible
      - (MOBILE ONLY) When focusing a "Node", its "Description" field becomes visible, even when empty
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) To toggle between "Node" and "Description" we can use `Shift+Enter`. Empty "Descriptions" are invisible
      - (MOBILE ONLY) When the virtual keyboard is visible while editing, the status bar remains above the keyboard
        Implemented via `window.visualViewport` resize events that apply a dynamic bottom inset to the status toolbar
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) When nothing is focused, `↑` focuses the last node and `↓` focuses the first node.
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) `Enter` creates a new node below the focused node.
        If it already has children, the new node becomes the first child.
        If it does not have children, it creates a node at the same level.
    + PASTE
      - Pasting into a "Node" text input:
        - Single-line content without a leading `-` or `+` bullet → native browser paste (inserts at caret)
        - Multi-line content, or content with a leading `-`/`+` bullet → parsed as VMD structure
          The pasted text is treated as a VMD fragment; new nodes are created as needed
      - Pasting into a "Description" textarea:
        - Always plain text paste — content is inserted at caret, never parsed as VMD
        - This applies regardless of whether the pasted text looks like bullet-formatted VMD
    + (DESKTOP ONLY) MULTI-SELECT
      - When a "Node" is focused, a multi-bullet selection can be expanded with the shortcuts `Shift+↑/↓`
        - Arrow up expands the selection to the previous "Node" of the same indentation level
        - Arrow down expands the selection to the next "Node" of the same indentation level
      - Multi-select is only possible on a single indentation level
        - Selecting a "Node" implicitly selects all its children
    + (DESKTOP ONLY) MOVE
      - "Nodes" can be moved with the shortcuts `Alt+↑/↓`
      - If multi-selection is active, Move also works as expected
    + COLLAPSE
      "Nodes" can hide and show their children by collapsing and expanding
      - When collapsed, the "Node" has a visual indicator on the bullet point that it contains children, but they are not visible
        Collapsed and has children: ○ (hollow circle, rendered as SVG)
        Otherwise: ● (filled circle, rendered as SVG)
      - To toggle expand and collapse there will be a visible ▶ or ▼ button at the end of each line
        Always visible on mobile, visible on hover for desktop
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) To toggle expand and collapse we can use `Ctrl+Space`
      - (DESKTOP ONLY, MULTI-SELECT) When multi-selected, and we use the `Ctrl+Space` shortcut
        - If all "Nodes" are collapsed, then they all expand
        - Otherwise they all collapse
    + ZOOM
      When zoomed in, a "Node" and all its parents are clearly seen in the "Breadcrumb"
      - Each segment of the "Breadcrumb" is clickable and will zoom into that "Node"
      - When zoomed, the text of the "Node" is not editable
      - The description is also visible and editable
      - The "Children" of the zoomed "Node" will behave the exact same way as if they were root "Nodes"
      - Clicking the bullet point of a node zooms into it
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) `Alt+→` zooms into a node, `Alt+←` zooms back out
        - Most browsers use `Alt+←` to go back in history, so zooms are kept as browser navigation history entries
        - The URL carries the ID of the zoomed "Node" as a hash fragment so it can be directly referenced
        - If the URL contains a node ID hash on load, the app zooms into that node automatically after unlock
          This applies to all storage modes: Memory, Local, Remote, and File (including new/empty files)
        - If the node no longer exists, the hash is ignored and the root is shown
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) On zoom, the first child is automatically focused
    + INDENT
      - Each "Node" can be indented and unindented individually
        `Tab` and `Shift+Tab` are the shortcuts for changing indentation level
      - (MOBILE ONLY) A swipe right/left gesture can be used for indentation
      - Order will be kept when indenting and unindenting. Take this sequence as an example:
        `     | INDENT B | INDENT C | UNINDENT B | INDENT B`
        `- A  | - A      | - A      | - A        | - A`
        `- B  |  - B     |  - B     | - B        |  - B`
        `- C  | - C      |  - C     |  - C       |   - C `
      - If multi-selection is active, indentation also works as expected
    + DELETE
      - "Nodes" can be deleted without confirmation when they don't have "Children"
      - A confirmation is necessary when "Children" exist. Deleting a "Node" also deletes all its "Children"
      - If multi-selection is active, delete also works as expected
      - The node is deleted if Backspace is pressed on a node that has no text
        If there is text, the backspace functions as if `↑` was pressed
      - (DESKTOP ONLY) The shortcut `Ctrl+Backspace` is used for delete
  + STORAGE MODES
    Four storage modes are available. The most appropriate one is selected automatically on each visit.
    - Memory — document lives only in JS memory; lost when the tab is closed. No passphrase, no account, no encryption.
      Default on the very first visit (no localStorage data, no remembered mode).
    - Local — document encrypted in-browser (localStorage). Passphrase created on first use. No account needed.
      Optional quick unlock can store a wrapped copy of the passphrase on this device.
    - Remote — document encrypted and synced to the cloud via Supabase.
      Account email, account password, and passphrase are required.
      Optional quick unlock can store a wrapped copy of the passphrase on this device.
    - File — document stored as plain VMD text in a local `.vmd` file via the File System Access API.
      No passphrase or account needed. Only available in browsers that support the API.
      The startup mode is determined as follows:
    + Rules for selecting a mode
      - No remembered mode and no existing data signals → Memory mode, INTRO.VMD loaded
      - Remembered mode is Local
        - local data present → Local unlock screen
        - no local data → Local unlock screen (create passphrase)
        - if quick unlock is saved for Local on this device, startup attempts Local auto-unlock before showing the lock screen
      - Remembered mode is Remote
        - valid session → Remote unlock screen (passphrase only)
          if quick unlock is saved for this Remote account on this device, startup attempts Remote auto-unlock before showing the lock screen
        - expired session → Remote unlock screen (email prefilled)
          quick unlock never bypasses account sign-in; after sign-in, it may satisfy only the passphrase step
      - Remembered mode is File, valid handle → File reopened silently; if permission denied → file picker
      - Any remembered mode overrides incidental data signals (leftover ciphertext, cached email)
        Switching modes may discard local data or sign out; a confirmation is shown when that would happen.
        The Options panel action label and confirm text are mode-specific so users understand what is and is not lost.
    + MEMORY MODE
      - On the very first visit the lock screen is bypassed; the app loads INTRO.VMD from `/intro.vmd`
        INTRO.VMD is a separate VMD file served alongside index.html — not embedded in JS
      - The status toolbar shows "In memory — not saved" instead of the mode label and sync dot
      - Raw mode is hidden (nothing to save)
      - Options shows an "Upgrade storage…" button that lets the user switch to Local, Remote, or File
        Switching from Memory requires confirmation (data loss warning) and shows the lock screen
      - Purge action in Memory mode reloads the intro document (returns to the initial memory state)
      - The lock screen has a "Skip — continue in memory" link at the bottom
        Clicking it bypasses the unlock form and loads the app in memory mode for the current session
        The remembered mode is not changed, so the next visit will show the lock screen again
    + FILE MODE
      - The user opens or creates a `.vmd` file on disk using the browser File System Access API
      - The document is read and written as plain VMD text — no encryption, no JSON wrapper
      - The last opened file handle is remembered in IndexedDB; on next visit the app tries to reopen it silently
      - Every write is debounced: changes are flushed to disk ~1 second after the last edit
      - If the API is not supported in the current browser, the File mode button shows an error
  + RAW MODE
    - Direct manipulation of the text is possible in a special "RAW" mode
    - This document is an example of a raw Virgulas document; by convention it has the extension .vmd
    - The `+` char means a collapsed node and the `-` char means an expanded node
    - To actually have the + or - char at the beginning of a line, use the escape char \
      \ shows the \ character, \+ and \- show the + and - characters. Escaping is only needed at the beginning of lines
    - Hierarchy is determined by relative indentation, not absolute column numbers
      A child node must have more leading whitespace than its parent; the exact amount is not significant
      Sibling nodes share the same indentation level relative to their parent
    - All lines that do not begin with + or - (after stripping leading whitespace) are descriptions of the previous node
      Indentation is not relevant on description lines; empty lines are ignored
    - When in RAW mode, the app is a plain text editor with a "SAVE" and a "CANCEL" button
  + SEARCH
    - Search can be done with simple substring matches
    - Search is activated with `Escape` when no node is focused on desktop and with the `Search` button in the status bar on mobile
      The search controls are hidden by default
    - Search can be dismissed with `Escape` again on desktop or with an `X` clear button
    - When searching, the document becomes read-only
    - When searching, there is a live highlight of all matched words
    - When searching, all nodes that match are expanded and visible; non-matching nodes are hidden
    - (DESKTOP ONLY) Search results are cycled with `Tab` and `Shift+Tab`
    - When focusing a result by pressing `Enter` or clicking it, the app auto-zooms into the closest
      collapsed ancestor of the matched node
    - Search is "smart case": lowercase-only input is case-insensitive; any uppercase letter makes it case-sensitive
    - A result counter showing current index and total is visible while searching
  + ENCRYPTION
    Applies to Local and Remote modes. File mode is unencrypted (plain VMD on disk).
    The passphrase is the single secret the user must know. It is never stored or transmitted.
    - A random PBKDF2 salt is generated once and stored in localStorage under `vmd_salt`
      This is the only value in localStorage stored in plaintext, as it is required to derive the key
    - The encryption key is derived from the passphrase and the salt via PBKDF2 (310,000 iterations, SHA-256, 256-bit output)
      The derived key is never stored — it is re-derived on each unlock
    - All document data is encrypted with the derived key using AES-GCM with a unique IV per write operation
      The IV is prepended to the ciphertext and stored together, base64-encoded
    - The encrypted document is stored in localStorage under `vmd_data`
    - If the passphrase is forgotten, encrypted data is unrecoverable. There is no cryptographic recovery path.
      A destructive reset path may replace remote encrypted data with a new empty document and a new passphrase.
    + QUICK UNLOCK (DEVICE-SCOPED)
      - Quick unlock is optional and available only in Local and Remote modes on compatible browsers
      - Quick unlock is enabled and disabled from the Options popup while unlocked
        There is no lock-screen opt-in for quick unlock
      - The passphrase itself is not stored in plaintext
        A locally wrapped passphrase blob plus credential metadata is stored on-device only
      - Quick unlock never changes the document encryption format and never changes server schema
      - Local quick unlock can auto-unlock on startup
      - Remote quick unlock can auto-unlock on startup only when the Supabase session is valid
      - When the Supabase session is expired, account sign-in remains mandatory
        Quick unlock can satisfy only the passphrase step after successful sign-in
      - If quick unlock recovery fails (unsupported, cancelled, stale, missing credential), the app falls back to manual passphrase entry
        Failures clear only the stale quick-unlock record; encrypted document data is not touched
      - Quick unlock records are scoped per mode, and for Remote they are additionally scoped per account identity
      - Removing quick unlock deletes only the saved device record
        It does not lock the app, delete encrypted data, or sign out
      - Replacing quick unlock is done by removing the saved device record, then enabling quick unlock again
      - On destructive passphrase reset flows, previous quick-unlock records are invalidated automatically
  + ACCOUNTS AND SYNC
    Creating an account enables cloud sync via Supabase. The encryption model is unchanged.
    The server stores only ciphertext and cannot decrypt user data.
    - The account password is only used for Supabase Auth — it is unrelated to the encryption passphrase
      The passphrase is set independently and never sent to any server
    - To create an account the user provides an email and password for Supabase Auth
      The PBKDF2 salt already in localStorage is uploaded to the `outlines` table
      From this point, any device that knows the passphrase can re-derive the same key
    - Signing in on a new device fetches encrypted payload + salt from the `outlines` table
      The user enters their passphrase, the key is re-derived, and the document is decrypted
      If account auth succeeds but decryption fails, the lock screen offers a destructive reset to replace remote encrypted data using a new passphrase
    - The derived key lives only in memory for the duration of the session
      On page close or sign-out, the key is gone and must be re-derived on the next visit
    + SYNC BEHAVIOUR
      - Before every local write, the app checks if the remote `updated_at` is newer than `lastSyncedAt`
        If the remote is newer, the remote document is fetched and merged before the local write is pushed
        This pull-before-push strategy ensures the server always receives the most up-to-date merged state
      - A background poll runs every 60 seconds while the app is open (in Remote mode)
        If the remote is newer and there are no pending conflicts, the remote is fetched and merged silently
        The poll pauses while conflicts are pending
      - Merge is performed at the node level using per-node `lastModified` timestamps and a single `lastSyncedAt` timestamp
        - Node modified only on one side since `lastSyncedAt` → that side wins, no user action needed
        - Node modified on both sides → per-field direct value comparison:
          - Same value → no conflict, either value is kept
          - Different value → conflict; the user must resolve it
          - `open` (collapse/expand) uses last-writer-wins (newer `lastModified`), never a conflict
        - Node added on one side only → kept
        - Node deleted on one side while unmodified on the other → deletion wins
        - Node deleted on one side but modified on the other → the modified side wins (deletion loses)
        - Root node is never deleted
        - After merge, any node whose parent is missing is dropped (tree integrity)
      - When conflicts exist, a blocking modal is shown; the app cannot be used until all conflicts are resolved
        Each conflict is displayed with the node text, field name, and side-by-side local / remote values
        Per-conflict: "Keep local" / "Keep remote" buttons; bulk: "Use all local" / "Use all remote"
        "Apply" is disabled until every conflict has a resolution; pressing it pushes the merged result
      - If the upload fails it is retried with exponential back-off (3 retries) then abandoned until the next write
      - The status toolbar shows a sync indicator while the user is signed in
        Possible states: synced, syncing, error, offline
    + DATABASE SCHEMA
      - `outlines` table
        - `user_id` uuid primary key — references auth.users
        - `salt` text — PBKDF2 salt, base64-encoded, generated on first use and never changed
        - `data` text — AES-GCM encrypted document, base64-encoded
          The first 12 bytes of the decoded value are the IV, the remainder is the ciphertext
        - `updated_at` timestamptz
      - Row Level Security enabled
        All policies restrict read and write to `auth.uid() = user_id`
  + Design considerations
    - A splash screen is seen on load, and it is removed after the app is completely ready
    - The text of root nodes has a font-size of 1rem, the second level 0.9rem, and remaining nodes 0.85rem
      The description has a more faded colour and is 85% of the size of the node text
    - There is a "Status" toolbar at the bottom of the screen with
      - "RAW" mode button
      - "?" button to show all keyboard shortcuts
      - "Options" button to see all configuration options
        - Theme toggle
        - A link to the source repository
        - A button to purge all local data and start fresh
      - A sync status indicator, visible only when the user is signed in
    - Google font Inter is the base typography. 1rem = 14px
      Base: 'Inter', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif;
      Mono: ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, Monaco, Consolas, "Liberation Mono", "Courier New", monospace;
  + Technical considerations
    - The app is a static website. No server is necessary to use it
    - The document is stored in localStorage as a single JSON object, always encrypted
    - Preact and Preact Signals are the UI frameworks, loaded via CDN import map
    - The Supabase JS client is loaded via CDN
    - All crypto operations use the native Web Crypto API
    - Playwright E2E tests cover all the app's features and edge cases
    - The app shell and all static assets are cached by a Service Worker (`sw.js`) on first load
      After the first successful load the app opens fully offline (no network required)
    - (DESKTOP ONLY) `Ctrl+Alt+D` toggles a developer panel at runtime
      - Sections: outline stats, focus/zoom/search state, sync diagnostics, crypto timings, storage quota, focused node raw JSON
      - Console debug messages are also printed while the panel is open
    + CI/CD
      - The app is hosted on GitHub Pages
      - On each commit, all E2E tests are run and a preview site is generated
      - On /preview, a page listing all open PRs is shown with a button to use that preview version
        E.g. `virgulas.com/preview/my-feature` will serve the code from the `my-feature` branch
      - On the main branch, the pipeline purges the Cloudflare cache after a successful deploy
      - Daily, a secondary workflow runs all tests against the production version at `virgulas.com`
  + ROADMAP
    Ideas and improvements under consideration. Nothing here is committed — items may be adopted, modified, or dropped.
    - Missing test coverage
      Existing tests cover the happy path well, but some SPEC behaviours still have no E2E coverage.
      Remaining gaps:
      - Service worker offline shell behaviour (real offline navigation / cached boot)
      - Zoom browser history (back/forward with hash-based zoom semantics)
      - Mobile search activation gesture (scroll-up)
      - Sync polling pause/resume while conflicts are pending, and additional merge edge cases
    + Feature ideas
      - Queued background sync: queue remote sync changes locally and execute them automatically once the connection is restored.
      - Load VMD document from querystring parameter. Either url of a vmd file or base64 encoded file text
      - Outline statistics: node count, word count, max depth — shown in Options or a status bar tooltip
      - Image attachments: support pasting or dragging images directly into nodes, uploading them to Supabase Storage (for Remote mode) or persisting as compressed base64 (for Local/File modes).
      - Tags (#) and Mentions (@):
        - **Autocomplete**: Typing `#` or `@` opens a dropdown suggesting existing tags/users to prevent typos.
        - **Sidebar/Dashboard**: A dedicated view showing tag frequencies and allowing complex filtering (e.g., show `#todo` AND `@alice`).
        - **Task Management**: Mentions can act as assignments, rolling up into a "My Tasks" or "Assigned to X" view.
        - **Collaboration hooks**: If multi-player sync is added, `@user` could trigger email/push notifications.
      - Multi-document workspaces: allow saving and easily switching between multiple named outlines, rather than forcing everything into a single monolithic document tree.
      - Drag-and-drop reordering: complement keyboard move with pointer-based reorder (current DnD tests use internal helpers, not real drag events)
      - Accessibility: ARIA tree roles, screen-reader announcements for focus, collapse, and zoom changes
      - Virtual scrolling: for outlines with thousands of nodes, render only the visible portion to keep the UI responsive
      - Node linking: internal references between nodes (e.g. `[[node-id]]` syntax) with click-to-zoom navigation
      - Undo/Redo stack: keep a history of structural and text edits (e.g., capped at 100 actions) to safely revert accidental deletions or complex tree moves using `Ctrl+Z` and `Ctrl+Shift+Z`.
      - Developer Panel expansion: extend the `Ctrl+Alt+D` panel with active signal dependencies graph and additional runtime diagnostics.
      - Task Management: native outliner-based task tracking. Support for `- [ ]` and `- [x]` syntax that renders as interactive checkboxes, plus a dedicated dashboard that rolls up incomplete tasks and integrates with `@mentions` for explicit assignments.
